-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - June 5
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Wed Jun 04, 2014 10:05PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 5 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- The central government has suspended applications for new free-trade zones in an attempt to cool the nationwide frenzy to compete for the special status given to Shanghai last year, a Communist Party magazine reports. (http://link.reuters.com/rug89v) -- Cheaper debt capital is available to mainland issuers who are willing to take a slightly different approach to marketing. That is the message from bankers looking to bring Chinese issuers to the United States. (http://link.reuters.com/tug89v) -- At least 10 companies are gearing up to launch initial public offerings this month after a pick-up in investor sentiment amid expectations of a policy easing by Beijing to spur economic growth. (http://link.reuters.com/vug89v)  THE STANDARD -- A fresh jury of nine was empanelled on Wednesday for the corruption trial of a former chief secretary and the co-chairmen of Sun Hung Kai Properties <0016.HK>. (http://link.reuters.com/byg89v) -- Annual distributable income of the Link Real Estate Investment Trust <0823.HK> jumped 14 percent to HK$3.83 billion ($494.01 million) amid soaring rents for both retail space and car parks. Chief executive George Hongchoy Kwok-lung said their shopping malls would suffer less from a cut in mainland visitor numbers as they have few luxury jewellery and watch stores. (http://link.reuters.com/kyg89v) -- One-third of mainlanders do not want to visit Hong Kong, fearing discrimination, a poll has found. The poll of 1,215 people by the Southern Weekly newspaper found that two-thirds, or 821, have no plans to visit Hong Kong within a year, while one-third said they do. (http://link.reuters.com/qyg89v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Ozner Water International Holdings Ltd plans to issue new shares at between HK$2.25 and HK$2.70 apiece in an initial public offering in Hong Kong, raising up to HK$1.14 billion ($147.04 million) to develop its water purifying business in second and third tiers Chinese cities.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Hong Kong developer Hopewell Holdings <0054.HK> bought a small residential site in Wanchai district for HK$233 million ($30.05 million), representing more than HK$16,000 per square foot. The price was 28 percent higher than a nearby residential site that was sold last year.